Here is an example of how to automatically generate a table of contents in LaTeX:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
...
\section{Methods}
...
\section{Results}
...
\section{Discussion}
...

\end{document}
```

The key things to note:

- `\tableofcontents` is used to generate the table of contents. This should be placed where you want the table of contents to appear in the document.

- Sections are defined using `\section{Title}` commands. 

- LaTeX automatically collects the section titles and page numbers and generates the table of contents when you compile the document.

- No need to manually enter contents into a table - it is generated automatically based on the `\section` commands.

- Compile the document twice for the page numbers to update correctly in the table of contents.
